In PostgreSQL, we can achieve similar semantics by explicitly casting the zero to real using '0::real'. This ensures that we maintain the same type and avoid any meaningless features, as required.

The error occurred because the value '1e100' exceeds the range of the 'real' type in PostgreSQL. By changing the cast to 'double precision', we can accommodate larger numbers without encountering an out-of-range error. The multiplication by zero remains the same, ensuring that we still adhere to the original semantics while satisfying the requirement to avoid meaningless features.
